	                <h1>
    	                <span id="Template_NewsDate1_lblDate" style="float:right">04 July 2012 16:16</span>

	                    Drugs operation, Scottish Borders


	                    <span id="Template_ctl08_lblMessage"><font color="Red"></font></span>

	                </h1>
                	
<p>Lothian and Borders Police have made a number of arrests as part
of a major drugs operation within the Scottish Borders.</p>
<table summary="box">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><img width="21" alt="Link" title="Link" src="/images/link_icon.jpg" height="21"/></td>
<td><a id="Template_ctl09_ctl00_linkToDocument" href="../../../../../pdf/Operation%20Goal.pdf" target="_blank">Operation Goal - tackling drugs and alcohol misuse (832KB pdf)</a></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><span><br />
Around 100 officers gathered at the Tweedbank Industrial Estate at
5.30am today (Wednesday) before carrying out raids at 11 addresses
in Galashiels, Selkirk, Kelso and Hawick.<br />
<br />
Today's activity was part of Operation Goal - a multi-agency
initiative to identify street-dealers and bring them to
justice.</span></p>
<p>Following over six months of intelligence gathering from the
local communities, nine men aged 49, 23, 29, 40, 42, 38, 31, 40 and
43 and two women aged 44 and 39 were all identified as being
involved in the distribution of drugs within the Borders.<br />
<br />
The information provided by the public provided police with
sufficient evidence to ensure all of these individuals were today
arrested and charged under the Misuse of Drugs Act.<br />
<br />
Additional street dealer amounts of Heroin and Valium, a cannabis
cultivation and personal quantities of cannabis were also recovered
as part of routine searches and a &pound;3000 individual cash seizure was
made.<br />
<br />
Following the enforcement phase, community officers will join
partners from NHS Borders and Scottish Borders Council to engage
with local residents and offer support and guidance to anyone
affected by the operation.<br />
<br />
A leaflet detailing today's action will be distributed within the
Borders communities and will also provide useful contact numbers
for local police, social work, housing departments and rehab
centres.<br />
<br />
The public will also be asked to remain vigilant for further
criminal activity in their area and report those who profit from
crime to police.<br />
<br />
Detective Chief Inspector Amanda McGrath, who had tactical command
for today's operation said: "Following receipt of confidential
intelligence from members of the public and concerns raised from
our partner agencies, my officers have conducted extensive
investigations into drug dealing across the Scottish Borders over
the last 6 months".<br />
<br />
"With the valued information from the public and support from our
partner agencies in bringing this initiative together, my officers
have been able to gain vital evidence and information, which has
successfully led to the arrest of these individuals".</p>
<p>"We are extremely fortunate to have an excellent working
relationship with our partner agencies and the willing assistance
and support we receive from members of the public cannot be
stressed enough.<br />
<br />
"We are committed to listening to our communities concerns and
putting in place targeted operations to keep the Scottish Borders a
safe place to live, to work and to visit. This is yet another fine
example of the invaluable help we receive from the community as a
whole".<br />
<br />
Dr Eric Baijal, Director of Public Health for NHS Borders and
Scottish Borders Council said: "This initiative continues the good
joint work of agencies towards preventing substance misuse and
minimising its impact on health and social wellbeing in
Borders.<br />
<br />
"The message is simple. If you or your family are involved in
substance misuse, this is an opportunity to change your life. Help
is available and there is a range of confidential support services
available for adults and young people across the Borders who wish
to seek help for a drug problem."<br />
<br />
Councillor David Parker, Leader of Scottish Borders Council said:
"The council is pleased to be working with Lothian and Borders
Police and NHS Borders on this operation.<br />
<br />
"Enforcement is obviously a key issue but that is not all that is
required. We need to make sure people are well supported and that
they know drug taking is not a route they have to go down."<br />
<br />
DCI McGrath added: "As we move through the summer months we will
continue our targeted operations which will result in further
arrests and I would like to take this opportunity to encourage
people within communities to come forward and report any form of
criminal activity to police.<br />
<br />
"Lothian and Borders Police are committed to reducing crime locally
within the Scottish Borders and providing re-assurance to our
communities".</p>
